  "text": "Comparison of Achilles tendon toxicity among fluoroquinolones. The changes to the Achilles tendon were as described previously [CITATION_1] . Briefly, edema with an increased number of mononuclear cells was often observed in the Achilles tendon sheath at the portion proximal to the tuber calcanei (Fig. 1) . In some cases, the lesions were more severe and extensive, involving the surface of the tendon tissue. In the synovial membrane adjacent to the lesions above, mild edema and an increased number of mononuclear cells were observed; with the latter associated tissue debris was also sometimes seen in the joint space. Dilation of blood vessels was found in association with edema in both the tendon sheath and the synovial membrane, but diapedesis of erythrocytes was not observed. Lesion incidence and estimated TD 50 s are presented in Table 1 . These tendon lesions were induced by 7 of the 10 fluoroquinolones tested. After the administration of single doses, fleroxacin and pefloxacin at 100 mg/kg or more induced Achilles tendon lesions; lomefloxacin, levofloxacin, and ofloxacin at 300 mg/kg or more induced lesions. Compared to the toxic potentials of these fluoroquinolones according to their TD 50 s, fleroxacin was most toxic, with a TD 50 of 176 mg/kg, followed by pefloxacin (212 mg/kg), levofloxacin (419 mg/kg), and ofloxacin (616 mg/kg), in decreasing order. The TD 50 of lomefloxacin, however, could not be determined because of an insufficient dose setting. Sparfloxacin and enoxacin at 900 mg/kg induced lesions. The incidence of lesions showed a dose-dependent trend for all these fluoroquinolones. In contrast, norfloxacin, ciprofloxacin, and tosufloxacin induced no lesions in the Achilles tendon.",
